  "prompt": "How can you determine the ionic charge of sodium?",
  "response": "To determine the ionic charge of sodium (Na), you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Locate Sodium in the Periodic Table**:\n   - Sodium is in **Group 1** (alkali metals) of the periodic table.\n\n2. **Understand Group 1 Elements**:\n   - Group 1 elements have **1 valence electron** in their outermost shell.\n\n3. **Determine the Charge**:\n   - To achieve a stable electron configuration (similar to the nearest noble gas, neon), sodium tends to **lose 1 electron**.\n   - Losing 1 electron results in a **+1 charge** because there is one more proton than electrons in the atom.\n\n4. **General Rule for Group 1**:\n   - All Group 1 elements form **+1 ions** when they lose their single valence electron.\n\nThus, the **ionic charge of sodium is +1**.",
